(Portions of two seals attached. 1. The Abbey of Tewkesbury. 2. The Abbot.)

This quittance by the Abbot and convent of Tewkesbury of the fine of 22s. (per annum) payable to them by Margam during the life of Jurdan de Hameledeu, is without date; the writing is apparently about end of the twelfth century, and therefore the document should take an earlier place in this series, neither is it known who J urdan was. Jurdan or Jordan was, however, a name in use in the allied Sandford and De Cardiff familie33 and a place called Hameleden is known to have descended from the former family to the latter in 1197. Jordan, therefore, may have been a De Cardiff or a Sandford.
